Description: ABL helps its Member CEOs grow great companies through confidential, collegial Round Tables & Events for Healthcare & Technology Leaders
Headquarters Regions: Greater Los Angeles Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: As California’s Premier Healthcare & Technology Executive Round Table Organization, ABL helps its Member CEOs grow great companies through its confidential and collegial monthly Round Tables and Events for Healthcare and Technology Leaders. Members draw on the Group’s peer-mentoring, strategic insights, and leveraged connections in these sessions, which are: Industry-specific; Professionally-facilitated; and Advisory board-like forums. For over 30 years, California’s Technology and Healthcare Executives have relied on ABL’s CEO Round Tables, through its peer advisory-board approach, to accelerate their corporate and professional growth and help them build great companies. In monthly, confidential sessions, ABL’s professional facilitators assure that Members are updated on the latest “best general business practices,” and enable the Members to leverage one another’s business savvy, as they apply lessons from the Group to their most pressing concerns. ABL supports the needs of its top-level Member Executives – the CEOs, Presidents, COOs, and Division GMs of venture-backed, privately held, and publicly traded companies – by providing them with a collegial setting in which to draw on the experience, knowledge and skill sets of their peers, who are in non-competitive sectors of the technology and healthcare industries. Leveraging ABL’s unique, industry-specific approach, Members share “What’s Keeping Them Up Nights” in the Round Tables, and gain feedback from each other on how they’re dealing (or have dealt) with those same issues. Together, ABL Members accelerate their real-time learning about how their peers are taking advantage of their industry’s emerging opportunities (and dodging its challenges), by: Sharing experiences; Learning new approaches; Rethinking their assumptions; Exploring opportunities; and Forging business relationships. Traits ABL Members have in common are: -A desire to grow their organizations more successfully -Recognition that fast-changing environments won’t allow for yesterday’s solutions to solve today’s (let alone tomorrow’s) problems -An openness to adapting approaches to their own firms that are working in other organizations, frequently very different from their own. Through this process, there’s an out-flowing of insights, ideas, and introductions, leveraging each Member’s time and investment. The broad spectrum of ABL Technology Members include the CEOs of licensed and cloud-based software and systems, hardware, B2B and B2C tech products, e-commerce, website design, SEO, and hosting, managed services and systems integration, 3D printing, instrumentation, engineering, optics, imaging, photonics, data and communications companies, tech-enabled manufacturers, and more. ABL’s Technology Round Tables are currently offered in Orange County, West Los Angeles, and the Downtown Los Angeles Area. The breadth of ABL Healthcare Members include leaders of non-profit, proprietary, publicly-traded, and governmental organizations. ABL’s Healthcare Round Tables are currently offered throughout California, in: San Diego, Orange County, Los Angeles, San Francisco, the East Bay, and Sacramento.

Full Description: Oxley's Extra is a new line of food and beverage products that are produced using beer (non-alcoholic) as an ingredient or as products likely to compliment and be consumed with beer. Each product is produced with just enough difference from every other existing product  currently on the market to give that all important ""unique selling proposition."" Everything from brand name, brand imagery, advertising slogan, advertising strategy has been developed over many years of research along with the intuitive likes of the end consumer - from sports to art to lifestyle preferences. Our target market is, obviously, beer drinkers.  All kinds of beer drinkers.  Millions of beer drinkers.  And while they all may have differing tastes in which beer or beers they prefer, they generally consume other food products while they are enjoying their beer of choice. What makes this effort even more unique is that every product will be produced by a leading supplier in the category of the specified product line.  Just to give one example; Oxley's Extra Potato Chips will be unique, from the type of potato used, the chip style and even the salt used.  They will be produced by one or more of the leading potato chip manufacturing companies in the country.   The companies producing the Oxley's Extra line of beer-related products will handle the sales and distribution of all Oxley's Extra products and be incentivized to by additional profits resulting form those incremental sales - sort of a reverse private-label program.  Oxley's Extra will handle the advertising and marketing of ALL Oxley's products. Catch a glimpse at www.oxleysextra.com

Description: Retailing is not dead! The Mattress business is thriving and is mostly recession proof.
Full Description: Retailing is not dead! The Mattress business is thriving and is mostly recession proof, and is a business that still depends mostly on brick and mortar locations to be successful: The first, most-important thing to know about a mattress is, Do you like how it feels? This year, one Mattress Retailer of Specialty Beds will top a billion dollars in revenue with no significant competition. If you want this unique mattress technology--this billion dollar technology--for all practical purposes,  you have only one place to go. More than 90% of this company's sales come from their Retail Stores. In the Portland, OR area, there are four stores in a fairly tight geographic region. These four stores should produce in excess of ten million dollars in revenue. (All figures and estimates taken from quarterly SEC filings). This market is ripe for one or two strong, properly-focused competing stores; DIRECT COMPETITORS, not conventional Mattress Stores that sell ""ordinary"" brands and products, or who merely dip their toe in with one or two ""me too"" products. That will be Sleeping On Air. This company sells an excellent, high profit-margin product, but there are  a few places where their business model is lacking. For example, dictated prices means no price negotiation, making them vulnerable to price competition from savvy, similar-product competitor. And all their mattresses are made-to-order; it takes up to two-weeks to get a bed. This makes them vulnerable to an In-stock, fast-delivery competitor.  They are also weak on after-the-sale service. A more nimble competitor could out-perform them easily, making unhappy customers very impressed with your service. This is a fantastic opportunity, with a realistic chance to grab 15% of the local market share in the first year, by providing comparable quality both faster and cheaper.The goal is to open one Sleeping On Air Store first, with a second location in 9-12 months. Recouping total investment in 12-18 months is very realistic.

Description: BRT Realty Trust (the Trust) originates and holds for investment senior mortgage loans secured by commercial and multi-family real estate
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: BRT Realty Trust (the Trust) originates and holds for investment senior mortgage loans secured by commercial and multi-family real estate property in the United States. The loans it originates are short term or bridge loans with a duration ranging from six months to one year. It lends at a floating rate of interest based on a spread over the prime rate and receives an origination fee for the loans it originates. It conducts its operations to qualify as a real estate investment trust (REIT), for federal income tax purposes. As of September 30, 2010, it had 12 senior loans outstanding, secured by properties located in six states, of which 70% were secured by properties located in the New York metropolitan area. As of September 30, 2010, its outstanding loans had an aggregate principal balance of $57.7 million and an average contractual interest rate of 9.5%.
